<br>
When attempted, Maxed warrior taunt skill has about a 25% success rate. On a sucess you're accumulated hate score gets set to whatever the top score is plus a smidge more, even if you already had the top score. So when taunt succeeds you always gain that smidge. Over time, those smidges add up and do make a difference in preventing folks from stealing agro in the first place. I suspect that even fails give you that smidge but don't also give you top score first.<br>
<br>
I don't mash taunt, I mash an <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Agro Combo</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> hotkey. The hotkey looks like this:<br>
<br>
/doability 7 (taunt skill)<br>
/doability 8 (bash or kick skill)<br>
/doability 9 (disarm)<br>
<br>
When taunt suceeds you move to the top of the hate list, plus you get bash agro (which btw is higher then kick due to the stun component) plus disarm agro (even if disarm doesn't succeed and/or the mob isn't armed). If taunt does not suceed you're still producing hate by mashing this key, which in the long run reduces the chance of your group mates getting agro from things like CH. Even if you're alrdy at the top of the hate list, mashing a combo key like this puts you higher on the list, maybe not from taunt but certainly from bash and disarm.<br>
<br>
If you're not taunting, disarming and special attacking every oportunity you get, the chances of higher DPS classes pulling agro are much higher. Mashing this combo allows me to reliably keep agro off a rogue delivering far more DPS and not using evade. And yes I tested this with low agro procing weapons so my ability to hold agro off the rogue wasn't due to procs, evade or DPS.<br>
<br>
The other thing to be aware of is the affect of proximity agro. The closer you are to a mob's agro point the higher you are on the hate list. A given mob's agro point is not always where you might think. For any given mob model, the agro point is that spot on the model it pivots on and is also that spot you actually run into when trying to move thru the mob. For instance on spider models its just in front of the head between the front legs and not in the abdoment like you might expect. Minimize the distance between you and the mob's agro point and you'll hold agro a lot better.<br>
<br>
On realy large mobs, this often means being literally inside the mob. Kunark Rhinos are the lowest lvl example of this I can think of. To maximize proxcimity agro on these, you need to be standing between the rhino's front legs.<br>
<br>
You can also use facing to your advantage. Place yourself between the mob and the party member most likely to pull agro (usualy the healer). This forces the mob to run over you to get to the healer, minimizing your distance in the process and maximizing your proximity agro. Often mobs will deagro the healer when they are  right up against you.<br>
<br>
Last little bit of advice, since your taunt key now has a bash (attack) component, you'll need another key for taunting mezzed mobs. Here's what I use:<br>
<br>
/doability 7 (taunt)<br>
/doability 9 (disarm)<br>
/doability 6 (beg)<br>
<br>
Both disarm and beg have a taunt component and don't break mez, so use them to save the chanter's life. 2 uses of this combo prior to breaking mez gives you agro about 80% of the time. 3 uses virtually gaurantees you agro on mez break.<br>
<br>
For what its worth, I play a 65 War with over 300 AAs that lvled the hard way, from scratch with no PL and virtually no twinkage (as well as several other toons). Not saying this makes me an expert or anything, just not some clueles noob/eBayed War. SKs and Pallies in my PoTime capable guild have bothered to comment on how well I hold agro dispite not being the best equiped tank.<br>
<br>
